<section xml:id="Eigenspaces">
  <title>Eigenspaces</title>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given <m>\mtx{A} = \left[ \begin{array}{rr} 3 \amp 0 \\ 8 \amp -1 \end{array} \right]</m> and <m>\vect{v} = \op{v_1}{v_2}</m>.
        Compute <m>\mtx{A} \vect{v} - 3\vect{v}</m> and <m>(\mtx{A} - 3 \mtx{I})\vect{v}</m>.
        What do you notice?
        What does it mean when <m>(\mtx{A} - 3 \mtx{I})\vect{v} = \vect{0}</m>?
        Find at least two vectors <m>\vect{v}</m> such that <m>\mtx{A}\vect{v} = 3\vect{v}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise> 
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given a square matrix <m>\mtx{A}</m>,
        when there exists a non-zero vector <m>\vect{v}</m> such that
        <m>\mtx{A}\vect{v} = \lambda \vect{v}</m> for some real number <m>\lambda</m> that vector is called an <term>eigenvector</term>
        for <m>\mtx{A}</m>,
        and <m>\lambda</m> its corresponding <term>eigenvalue</term>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <example>
  <p>
    <term>Example.</term> The effect of multiplication by a matrix on a representative set of vectors is illustrated below.
    Shown is a set of vectors and then those same vectors with the result of multiplying each of them by <m>\mtx{A} = \left[ \begin{array}{rr} 3 \amp  0 \\ 8 \amp  -1 \end{array}  \right]</m>.
    <figure>
	<sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
		<image source="Eigen1" ><description> Set of vectors. </description></image>
		<image source="Eigen2" ><description> Vectors moved by A. </description></image>
	</sidebyside>
	</figure>
	
	The vectors <m>\op{0}{1}</m>  and <m>\op{1}{2}</m>  are eigenvectors.
    Any scalar multiple of these vectors is also an eigenvector.
    The eigenvalue corresponding to <m>\op{0}{1}</m>  is
    <m>\lambda= -1</m> and the eigenvalue corresponding to <m>\op{1}{2}</m> is <m>\lambda = 3</m>.
  </p>
  </example>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given <m>\mtx{A} = \left[ \begin{array}{cc} 1 \amp  3 \\ 4 \amp  2 \end{array}  \right]</m>,
        find all values for <m>\lambda</m> such that the matrix equation
        <me>
          (\mtx{A} - \lambda \mtx{I})\vect{v} = \vect{0}
        </me>
        has a solution other that other than <m>\vect{v} = \vect{0}</m>.
        These are the eigenvalues for <m>\mtx{A}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given <m>\mtx{A} = \left[ \begin{array}{rrr} 2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp 0 \amp -1 \end{array} \right]</m> has eigenvalues
        <m>\lambda_\vect{v} = 2</m> and <m>\lambda_\vect{w} = -1</m>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Describe the set of vectors <m>\vect{v}</m> such that <m>\mtx{A}</m><m>\vect{v}</m> = 2<m>\vect{v}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Describe the set of vectors <m>\vect{w}</m> such that <m>\mtx{A}</m><m>\vect{w}</m> = -1<m>\vect{w}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <p>
    <question>
    If an eigenvector could be zero what would the corresponding eigenvalue be?
	</question>
  </p>
  <theorem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For any <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>\mtx{A}</m>,
        the set of eigenvectors corresponding to a given eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m> becomes a subspace of
        <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> if you include <m>\mathbf{0}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <proposition>
	<statement>
      Given matrix <m>\mtx{A}</m> has eigenvector <m>\vect{v}</m> with eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m> and <m>k~\in~\mathbb{R}</m>. 
	  What are the eigenvectors and eigenvalues of the matrix <m>k\mtx{A}</m>? What can you say about the eigenvectors 
	  and eigenvalues of the matrix <m>\mtx{A}^k</m>? Does it matter what <m>k</m> is?
	</statement>
  </proposition>
</section>